<br>
There are countless folks at varying stages of all quests, you cannot expect the quests to go away because you have killed the final NPC. It is a treadmill that cannot stop.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Well, I am not saying that EverQuest's brand of questing is &quot;wrong&quot;, but I do think it's not as conducive to roleplaying as it could be.<br>
<br>
In a multiplayer persistent world, I think it's silly to have automated quest dialog that treats the player as if he/she is the only hero/villain/adventurer in it.  I personally would prefer somewhat more generic quests if they have better continuity with the reality of the game world.  Epic, legendary, once in a lifetime events should not happening every week.<br>
<br>
And just because a world may designed to be dynamic doesn't mean some &quot;essential&quot; services wouldn't be preserved through thick and thin.  Newbies will always need a relatively safe place to spawn and learn the game, and I would agree that a world that is so constantly in flux that it becomes difficult to run basic errands because you can't find a friendly merchant would probably throw the casual gamer for a loop.  However, with good design, you can provide these &quot;staples&quot; in a dynamic world and still have the world in motion.<br>
<br>
I would mainly point at two games that seem to take an approach I'd advocate for creating a more authetic, interesting, roleplay-friendly atmosphere: <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://shadowbane.ubisoft.com"><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Shadowbane</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> and <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.gemstone.net"><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> GemStone III</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->.<br>
<br>
I haven't played Shadowbane yet (it's still in closed beta), but it appears to me that they are going out of their way to cater to the roleplaying element in a number of ways.  No, I don't hold any illusions that this is going to be a roleplayer's utopian mecca... but I do think that in several key areas, it will appeal to roleplayers on a level that EQ just isn't capable of reaching.  First, the game is being designed with one core principle idea in mind: the fate of the world shall lie in the hands of the players.  The boarders of kingdoms and empires, the welfare of each city, the economy region to region, all will be determined by player actions.  While this will certainly appeal to powergamers and others uninterested in roleplay, it also provides for an unlimited number of roleplayed scenarios that will be amount to much more than /duels and the occassional scripted ritual or wedding ceremony.<br>
<br>
Secondly, if you just read the background story and other information available on the game world, it is clear that they spent a <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> great</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> deal of effort creating a rich history for the world, but not only that, an excellent explanation of the state of the world, the nature of life and death, each of the playable races, and an overview of the gods, while still leaving a lot of the story as an untold mystery that may or may not be revealed as the world ages.  The story is great, but what is more important than story in a virtual world is the backdrop, the setting.  It has to be rich and full of character, and there can't be crucial missing details.<br>
<br>
I think GemStone III does an excellent job of providing a tremendous backdrop for roleplay, and countless details that one can use to flesh out their character.  The world is relatively static, but the chances are fairly good that if you want to you can participate in minor events that may occur, like fighting off an invasion of orcs, or playing a minor role in the mystery and drama of a brilliant and eccentric halfling wizard and his dark dealings with a demigod of pain, or assisting the prosecution or defense of an alchemist who is being blamed for the difficulties that wizards everywhere have been having creating enchanted items.  Are any of these deeds particularly epic or memorable?  Maybe yes, maybe no.  I do know however that from such &quot;quests&quot; and events, many players have had their characters elevated to a certain level of fame and notoriety and in many ways, Elanthia (the realm GS3 takes place in) does have a living history despite the fact that lasting, major changes to existing game content (in the form of lairs/towns being sacked and taken over) are pretty rare.<br>
<br>
I guess my point is, so what if the vast majority of players are oblivious to the &quot;story&quot; behind the game?  The &quot;story&quot; that most roleplayers are worried about is the story of <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> their own</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> characters, not Firiona Vie and Thubr Axebringr, and other characters and adventures they'll probably never play any direct part in. <p><B><FONT FACE="Comic Sans MS">--Tukka</FONT></B><BR>
Player of <A HREF="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=189682">Velsor Secarne</A> (on Firiona Vie)
<BR>
Shadow Knight of Cazic-Thule<BR>
Seeker of the Dark Truth
