<br>
If it doesn't move then it may not move with you, but at least it cannot move against you. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/utukka.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tukka</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 199<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(9/24/02 12:24:12 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2762.topic&index=29>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.atlantic.net/~tukka/glowhand.jpg height=44 width=44></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Carthage</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  The static nature may be less conducive to your roleplay, but what is events were moved in a direction that cut across your roleplay. With a fixed backdrop you at least know where you are. If - to take an acknowledgely extreme example - VI decided that the world had moved on and Dark elves and high elves were reconciled (I did say extreme example) then half the world just lost their reason for existence, or at least would be forced to adjust to circumstances moving in a direction directly contrary to their chosen role.<br>
<br>
If it doesn't move then it may not move with you, but at least it cannot move against you.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
First of all, only a very idiotic game designer would make such an extreme change to the state of the world as to invalidate peoples' roleplay.  However, I do not even necessarily see how the &quot;extreme change&quot; that you use an example would be any more hindering to roleplay than a completely static world.  Alliances shift, moods change, new things happen.  Roleplaying a dark elf or high elf who clings to old prejudgices and holds old grudges, while the rest of his/her society is moving towards a more cooperative and accepting attitude, would still be a <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  completely</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> valid character to roleplay and in many ways it could only but open more oppurtunities and scenarios for you to enjoy as a roleplayer.  So you wouldn't be the stereotypical dark elf/high elf anymore, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  what's wrong with that?</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Some of life's greatest dramas arise from how different people deal with change.<br>
<br>
 <p><B><FONT FACE="Comic Sans MS">--Tukka</FONT></B><BR>
