<BR>Officer of the <A HREF="http://www.indigovoid.net">Indigo Void</A></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/utukka.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tukka</A> at: 9/24/02 12:29:41 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ucobra102.showPublicProfile?language=EN>cobra102</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 48<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(9/25/02 2:30:30 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2762.topic&index=30>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Carthage</span><hr size=1> Yes, Tukka, it would be perfectly possible to roleplay through such an upheaval and to do it very well. However the real thrust of that change (which I agree would take a complete imbecile in game design ) was that it forced a direction of change upon players that might not suit large numbers of them. I can think of many who would feel uncomfortable with large scale changes and making the majority of your paying customers uncomfortable in order to stimulate the few is  poor business.<br>
<br>
And there I am afraid is your larger problem. We struggle to keep RP alive on FV, one of 20+ servers. The blue server population would have screaming fits if Freeport disappeared or the like. It is bad enough if they change a spawn rate, let alone dispense with it altogether. If there were a growing number of RP-preferred servers then our constituency would be greater for such changes. Heck, they couldn't even keep &quot;dynamic events&quot; going on SH and they had folks paying extra for them. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/utukka.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tukka</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 203<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(9/25/02 1:48:03 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2762.topic&index=31>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.atlantic.net/~tukka/glowhand.jpg height=44 width=44></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Carthage</span><hr size=1> Well, my basic argument is that EverQuest was designed with little heed or consideration given to roleplay.  I think this is evident in zone design, character design, the game's backstory, the nature of scripted events, the nature of quests and the way the game has been marketed.<br>
<br>
People don't care about roleplay in large part because the game was not designed for roleplayers.  Even people who are inclined to roleplay (such as myself) have pretty much given up on it in EverQuest.<br>
<br>
As far as I'm concerned, there is very little they can do to improve the climate for RP without alienating the bulk of their customer base.  The original question posed was why people feel EQ lacks a coherant narrative, and I guess my answer is that the narrative that we all experience in the form of quests and general game environment is non-conducive to RP... it just serves as a adequate platform from which to launch various challenges.<br>
<br>
I know that by playing to the masses, Verant has pretty intentionally set down this road.  One of the rules of a virtual world is that the quality of roleplaying is inversely proportional to the number of players.   Oh well.  I'm not saying it's bad business sense, I'm just pointing out how this game is clearly not designed with roleplaying as a focus and how it is clearly lacking in this regard.<br>
<br>
I still think that there are things that they could have done (and they probably realize this in retrospect, hindsight is 20/20) to encourage and faccilitate roleplaying without alienating the masses, but it's too late to change things now. <p><B><FONT FACE="Comic Sans MS">--Tukka</FONT></B><BR>
Player of <A HREF="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=189682">Velsor Secarne</A> (on Firiona Vie)
<BR>
Shadow Knight of Cazic-Thule<BR>
Seeker of the Dark Truth
<BR>Officer of the <A HREF="http://www.indigovoid.net">Indigo Void</A></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uthevolcanogod.showPublicProfile?language=EN>thevolcanogod</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 80<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(9/25/02 2:05:33 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2762.topic&index=32>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> VI's Failure</span><hr size=1> One of the things that could have helped the situation was the idea of GM events. They used to happen quite often and there were some pretty fun ones. I missed most of the &quot;War of the Gods&quot; GM event line because I decided to take a break half way through, but it started out pretty cool. I remember lots of GM events &quot;back in the day&quot;. Killer Chickens in DL, Faydedar (or whatever his name is - that fish in TD) in the Lake of Ill Omen, Countless undead invasions of various zones, Scarecrow invasions, Mayong Mistmoore etc. Besides that Friday the 13th battle event, I haven't seen or heard of any other GM events in the couple months I have been back. <br>
<br>
Even though they were kinda lame, GM events used to be very cool. People would run half-way across the world to attend and all of the EQ fan sites would list them and the results after they happened. This was one way where VI could have kept a non-static content going but dropped the ball. It went the way of CS. Instead of enriching the gameplay of the product they had they put all of their energy into adding to it. If I had to choose between lame GM events where a bunch of killer chickens invade the Dreadlands and nothing, I would choose lame GM events.<br>
Vulrath <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ustrayvz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Stray VZ</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 30<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(9/25/02 2:36:50 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2762.topic&index=33>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.wannabebigforums.com/avatar.php?userid=2617&dateline=1027035878 WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: VI's Failure</span><hr size=1> GM events where great...but soon where ruined by bickering and the &quot;uber&quot; guilds coming in and taking over as soon as they had found out about them.<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ubreoghan.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Breoghan</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(9/28/02 4:16:22 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2762.topic&index=34>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: VI's Failure</span><hr size=1> Which would you rather have?<br>
<br>
1. A fairly rich and detailed backstory that is learned in as bits and pieces here and there throughout the game.  Coupled with a game world that doesn't force you into any particular storyline.<br>
<br>
2. A website that details all the rich history of the world and which is basically required reading to understand what the point of the game is.  An on-going storyline which you will be thrust into the moment the game starts, and have no chance to affect.<br>
<br>
The second option is the approach Neocron, Shadowbane, and Asherons Call 2 are taking.  There's nothing wrong with that, but playing a forced role in someone else's story isn't how I want to roleplay.  It's too much like playing Diablo or Final Fantasy; no matter what you do, the story is going to proceed through a pre-determined and already-written plot. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ubreoghan.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Breoghan</A> at: 9/28/02 4:17:17 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ugrimjesta.showPublicProfile?language=EN>GrimJesta</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 10<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(9/28/02 1:15:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2762.topic&index=35>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Why do people feel EQ doesn't have a &quot;coherent narr</span><hr size=1> So I read this post last night and went to bed thinking about it. <br>
<br>
I dont think its possible for them to have a coherent, connected plot that everyone is involved in. Why? Le,mme tell ya a story:<br>
<br>
Long ago (not really) Vampire the Masquerade Redemption came out. It had multiplyer capabilities, so I figured I would be getting some hardcore World of Darkness action going on. It had a build in die-roller, so you didnt have to use the crappy game engine, loads of maps and cool skins. They released the map editor too and loads of skin editors came out. I was excited.<br>
<br>
Until my first game. I honestly thing all the d00dz from the PvP EQ server bought Vampire:redemption and took over. EVERY game was basically the &quot;storyteller&quot; populating the maps like a video game and letting the characters run through killing everything and gaining XP. All were totally tweaked out. It was a nightmare.<br>
<br>
Then I found this one guy named Vandle. He told me he had about six other people that were into using the game engine for a persistent, hardcore, all roleplay game-world that actually followed the World of Darkness. <br>
<br>
Well, 6 people became 70 in no time, as every hardcore player wanted in. We actually had to start rejecting applications. Soon Vandle left and I found myself one of the people in charge. I was the main plot-writer and world-molder I guess you could say. I wound up creating this insane plot filled with intruiges and manipulations worthy of any Vampire game.It was hardcore. The other STs and admin read it and said, &quot;wow.&quot;<br>
<br>
Keep in mind there were only 70 players, not the near 500,000 EQ has.<br>
<br>
We introduced the story, set up the NPCs. We made it possible to not partake in the plot, but it would still affect the world around them. And unlike EQ, the only way top  gain XP is to RP. And people chose to ignore the plot for the most part. They all had their own agendas, their own reasons for doing things. Our plot, to many, was just the justification to introduce new NPCs or minor events for them to attend to.<br>
<br>
This is what I can see happening if the GMs ever went through the HELL (and yes, its a hell) of writing an online plot of any hardcore type. I can see the yellow text popping up from the GM's telling us of some new plot unfolding. New events would occur. <br>
<br>
And people would keep hunting wherever they are hunting. The events would hardly make it into roleplay because I am hardpressed to find roleplayers on the RP server. Aye, I knoiw theres a ton out there, but not enough to justify a major plot-line. The plot would go from Verant justifying new zones and NPCs to most players using it to justify new raids, NOT for roleplaying.<br>
<br>
It seems that everyone here is hardcore into roleplaying. But I have still met way too many on the RP server that were d00dz or WORSE. So it wouldnt be worth the GMs time to create this huge plot. The rewards would not outweigh the work.<br>
<br>
This is just my opinion on it all. But it is an opinion based upon experience in GMing an online game.<br>
<br>
The only thing I can say is that it is up to us. Look at our real world. If you look at it from far away, like if there was a game manual for it, things here would also seem hardly connected and half-assed if you took the people out. But its the people doing their thing and creatuibng their own sagas and legends that makes it cool.<br>
<br>
So do the same thing in EQ. Sure, the backstory isnt all the fleshed out. But I bet YOUR story is! And I bet people you know have hardcore stories. And they know people with hardcore stories. So why not bring it up into roleplay. Mention places youve been to, but not as a zone. Mention it as a living breathing place. Mention people you know, but in a realistic way. Speak of events youve encountered. Aye they never REALLY took place, but who will condemn you for speaking of a small riot in the Freeport market district? Who would really complain if you spoke of strange lights in Greater Faydark at night. <br>
<br>
Its up to us. Verant/Sony gave us the tools. The computer is the canvas. WE are the artists. And Firiona Vie, being the RP server, is all the Picassos and Michaelangelos. Or we are supposed to be.<br>
<br>
So, what say you?<br>
<br>
 <p>-=Aarchus Xhar'Gothe, the Hand of Innoruuk=-

